    <item>
      <title>14.14 Starvation</title>
      <link>https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-14-starvation/</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-14-starvation/</guid>
      <pubDate>Sat, 14 Dec 2024 03:12:59 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;main class="wp-block-group is-layout-flow wp-block-group-is-layout-flow"&gt; &lt;div class="wp-block-group is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"&gt;&lt;h1 class="wp-block-post-title"&gt;14.14 Starvation&lt;/h1&gt;   &lt;div style="height:1px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;div class="entry-content wp-block-post-content is-layout-constrained wp-block-post-content-is-layout-constrained"&gt; &lt;p&gt;(&lt;a href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-13-tomato/"&gt;Previous Chapter&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao was at the weirdo tactician&amp;#8217;s residence.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;She honestly didn’t want to come, but she had to.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“You’re a part of this, I see.&amp;#8221; &lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Rather than a part of this, I was forced to take part.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Isn’t it always like that?” Yao who came to greet Maomao made a look of surprise.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Today, both Yao and En’en were on break, and Maomao specially took leave as well. People might raise an eyebrow at having three court physician assistants take a day off together, but it can’t be helped. What’s more, when Court Physician Liu was told that it was the imperial brother’s orders, he agreed to her leave with a look of disgust. Since the old court physician, that is Court Physician Lao, has headed for the smallpox front-lines, she had to get all sorts of permissions from Court Physician Liu.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao wanted the old court physician to return soon.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Anyway, come this way. Essentially, En’en and I will be looking after her. Luomen-sama would be coming shortly, it seems,” Yao said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Do you know when?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao also rarely saw Luomen. He pretty much resided in the inner palace. Although eunuchs didn’t face as many restrictions as palace ladies did when it came to entering and exiting the inner palace, he must be holding back from leaving as there were new high-ranking consorts and the quack doctor wasn’t dependable.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I wonder. I heard it would be in a few days’ time.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao made a sullen face. She wanted to see Luomen, but not the weirdo tactician. She wondered what she should do. “Well, for the time being, where is the patient?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“She is near our outbuilding. En’en is currently preparing meals, but…”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“But?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Is that child, really a young lady from a good family?” A look of disbelief faced Maomao.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Umm, I believe the patient is a fourteen year old malnourished girl.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“That is certainly the case.” Yao eyed the outbuilding.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“You can&lt;em&gt;not&lt;/em&gt;!”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;That shriek belonged to En’en. Maomao blinked in surprise. That woman never raised her voice.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao and Yao rushed over to the outbuilding where the patient was.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;And there was a panicked En’en raising a large pot high over her head. Zhizi was clinging onto the woman, trying to snatch away that pot. There were traces of congee around the girl’s mouth.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“She is more of a starved feral child than a young lady raised in tender care,” Yao said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“So I see,” Maomao said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Come to think of it,&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;She did hear that Zhizi had been so starved she once tried to eat a frog in the garden.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“She looked a little more prudent to me, though.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;Where&lt;/em&gt;?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;She had been quite weakened from malnutrition and poison when Maomao met her the other day. Looks like she just hadn’t been resisting due to her declined health.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Don’t just &lt;em&gt;watch&lt;/em&gt;. Do something!” En’en said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao and Yao hurried to pull Zhizi off En’en. That once-quiet girl let out an incredible beast-like groan.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Food. Food. &lt;em&gt;Please&lt;/em&gt;!”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Zhizi’s voice was child-like but pressing. The moment Maomao saw the girl’s ribs from her opened nightgown and her stick-thin arms and legs, she no longer wanted to let the girl eat her fill.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao, Yao, and En’en wanted to do what they could. And an expert who was related to supplying food to one more person was also watching stealthily.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Will you not feed her?” Rahan’s older brother said with a look of anxiousness. The basket carried over his back contained root vegetables.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“As much as we would love to feed her, we can’t,” Maomao said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Why not?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“She could die if you suddenly give her sustenance while she’s in a state of starvation.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&lt;em&gt;Die&lt;/em&gt;?!” Rahan’s older brother surreptitiously put away the turnip he was about to take out.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes. A long time ago, a castle had its supply of food cut off by the enemy…”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Hit by starvation tactics, the people were forced into famine. When the starved were finally released, they devoured congee with wild abandon. Then they dropped like flies.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was a story she heard from Dad. She also instructed Yao and En’en through the letter. En’en was faithfully playing her part.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Couldn’t it be because the congee was poisoned?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Not at all. Those who ate the congee slowly survived. While I do not know the cause, could it be that their stomachs had gone into the highest state of shock?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I won’t be able to get over dying from shocking your stomach.” Rahan’s older brother set the basket of turnips in a place out of sight. Zhizi’s blazing eyes were looking around for food.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“And so, with her current condition, she could die if she eats as much as she wants. We will be increasing her portion little by little, so please endure.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;However, Maomao and Yao were holding Zhizi back as the girl reached for the pot of congee. “I have to eat now. I don’t know when it&amp;#8217;s the next time I get to eat!”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“You will get to eat! I’ll give it to you for lunch in two dual-hour’s time!”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The girl didn’t believe En’en. Zhizi was like a stray dog who wasn’t done being fed. That alone was enough to tell all the long years she had suffered.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I can’t abandon her.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao thought she had gone soft. There were so many starving children in the world. If Maomao saved them all, she herself would die a dog’s death. Thus, she had decided to abandon them and turn a blind eye.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;And now, the reason she couldn’t abandon Zhizi was because if it was just the girl alone, she could save her at least.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao took out a dried cuttlefish from her bosom pocket. “Please chew on this and endure for the time being.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“AH!” Zhizi took the dried cuttlefish from Maomao and started to chew on it like a dog with a bone.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Whew.” En’en took away the remainder of the congee.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Rahan’s older brother left in a hurry as if he thought he said too much. He mostly likely came over with vegetables as support because En’en was there, but it wasn’t the time for it.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Then, get a good sleep. I’ll wake you up when it’s time for food.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Zhizi showed no indications of having heard or not. She was intently licking the dried cuttlefish. Maomao wanted interview the child, but it would be better if she was little more calm.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;There was a table and chairs in front of the patient’s room. Maomao and Yao automatically went to sit on the chairs.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Are you monitoring her?” Maomao asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes, you’d have to with how she is. We caught her heading over to the kitchen last night,” Yao said.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;A hopeless problem child.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao felt apologetic, but Yao didn’t look annoyed.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yao-san.” Maomao made sure that En’en wasn’t around. With how meticulous that woman was, she was probably scrubbing the pot clean. “I think you have been at this residence for long enough. Do you have any thoughts about it?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“That’s quite a roundabout way of putting it.” Yao stretched widely. “I don’t know myself either. I don’t know, but I’m stuck. Then I think about how I can make myself leave at this stage… but I somehow get so frustrated I can’t do it.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao also stretched widely. Normally she would be in the opposite position. Chue would be the one asking Maomao.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;It would be nice if Chue-san could do this for me.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao thought, but Chue probably wouldn’t do it. While Chue talked because it was Maomao, she probably won’t talk to Yao. The woman got carried away and was agreeable to anyone, but beyond Maomao, she dealt with human relationships logically.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;And Yao didn’t know Chue either. She wouldn’t necessarily lend an ear to Chue’s words.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao was also worried over whether her own words reached Yao. But Yao, in her own way, was more mature than she was in the past.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Maomao would have probably already realised, but I’ll be honest. I’m happy that Zhizi-san came here. It’s a lot of work, but I end up thinking that it’s fine for me to be here because of her. I am a hopeless, immature person with bad thoughts. While I complain that it’s a lot of work, I think if Zhizi-san is hopeless, it’ll be even better for me.” Yao spoke softly. It was at a volume that Zhizi who was at the back of the room couldn’t hear.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Yao may seem dignified, but apparently she had no self-confidence. Hence she sought to be depended upon to gain self-confidence. &lt;em&gt;It’s fine if she’s self-aware&lt;/em&gt;, Maomao thought.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao had an idea where Yao’s lack of self-confidence stemmed from.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;The incident with the Sha’ou priestess, huh.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Yao had previously been the food taster for the Sha’ou priestess. Consequently, her organs were damaged as a result of the priestess’s scheme and even now she could no longer eat foods with strong flavours.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Yao had been used. She wasn’t at fault. But due to political decisions, she was forced to take on a bad reputation.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The Sha’ou priestess who survived was officially treated as deceased. She stayed behind in Li, and will not appear on the centre stage from now on.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Consequently, Yao became someone who failed at food tasting and had an important person from a foreign country die. Since Yao’s life was also in danger at one point, no one would openly criticise her. But the one who felt the most responsibility was Yao.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I can’t say anything either.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao couldn’t speak the truth. It would be good if she could, but she mustn’t.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I understand what Maomao is trying to say. I, too, will be leaving this estate once Zhizi-san gets better,” Yao said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Is that so?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“But don’t tell En’en yet, please. She may rush Zhizi-san who needs the time to recover slowly.” Yao viewed En’en with composure. Yao wasn’t going to stay the same forever too.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I think Yao-san is doing well.” Maomao could only tell her like this.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The girl was only seventeen years old. She had a variety of paths open to her, and yet she became a court physician assistant in defiance of her uncle.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Honestly, the path was filthy, stinky and tough. She was walking the exact opposite path of other court ladies who were working in the imperial court for bridal training. She didn’t admit defeat immediately and still continued with it, even now practicing so that she would be taught surgery.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yao-san is better off going to more places. Meet all sorts of people, get all sorts of experience. But being a court physician assistant, I think you have a lot more experience than normal women, though.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;At her current location, Yao didn’t realise that she was capable herself. Honestly, if she went to other departments, she would probably be regarded highly in no time.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I can’t fly about like Maomao does.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Is that how you take me as?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It seems Yao had no intention of leaving the doctor’s path.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Well, there is an aspect of me that is somewhat like a jack of all trades.” Maomao would have preferred to be a little more grounded, but she was just flying about. She didn’t get called up this time since it was related to smallpox, but she had no idea what could come up next.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;She couldn’t make up her mind about whether she should talk to Yao about things that were more sensitive, but she decided to stop here. If she spoke too much, it would be a mistake. This was something Maomao messed up often. “I wonder if Yo-san who disappeared off somewhere is doing okay right now.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“She went to the smallpox site, didn’t she? I heard Yo won’t contract it, though.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&amp;#8230;Yes. She has contracted it before.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“So she always wears long sleeves because she contracted smallpox before.” Yao gave a huge sigh. “Would they let me join them if I contract it once?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It’s better you stop here. There’s no safe way to contract smallpox.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;So far.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao recalled the man who covered half of his grinning face. Kokuyou would have gone to the same location as Yo and the others.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It would be groundbreaking if they could catch smallpox via Kokuyou’s master&amp;#8217;s method.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;If that were possible, they wouldn’t have as much hardship as now.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Let’s try sending a letter to Kokuyou.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;She didn’t know if she would get a reply, but Maomao wanted a different perspective than the regular correspondence from the court physicians.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity" /&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sub&gt;T/N: Random thought, but can you catch smallpox from a letter?  I&amp;#8217;ve heard about blankets and whatnot, but a letter?&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p class="has-text-align-right"&gt;(&lt;a href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-15-letters/"&gt;Next Chapter)&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div id="jp-post-flair" class="sharedaddy sd-like-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="sharedaddy sd-sharing-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="robots-nocontent sd-block sd-social sd-social-official sd-sharing"&gt;&lt;h3 class="sd-title"&gt;Share this:&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="sd-content"&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li class="share-facebook"&gt;&lt;div class="fb-share-button" data-href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-14-starvation/" data-layout="button_count"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li class="share-end"&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-130534757-5170-6767064be97bc' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/index.html?ver=20241221#blog_id=130534757&amp;amp;post_id=5170&amp;amp;origin=shikarito.wordpress.com&amp;amp;obj_id=130534757-5170-6767064be97bc' data-name='like-post-frame-130534757-5170-6767064be97bc' data-title='Like or Reblog'&gt;&lt;div class='likes-widget-placeholder post-likes-widget-placeholder' style='height: 55px;'&gt;&lt;span class='button'&gt;&lt;span&gt;Like&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class='loading'&gt;Loading&amp;#8230;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;span class='sd-text-color'&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;a class='sd-link-color' href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-14-starvation/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/main&gt;</description>
