    <item>
      <title>14.12 Spell</title>
      <link>https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-12-spell/</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-12-spell/</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 06 Dec 2024 10:58:35 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;main class="wp-block-group is-layout-flow wp-block-group-is-layout-flow"&gt; &lt;div class="wp-block-group is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"&gt;&lt;h1 class="wp-block-post-title"&gt;14.12 Spell&lt;/h1&gt;   &lt;div style="height:1px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;div class="entry-content wp-block-post-content is-layout-constrained wp-block-post-content-is-layout-constrained"&gt; &lt;p&gt;(&lt;a href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-11-the-safflower-3/"&gt;Previous Chapter&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“My goodness, it’s turned into such a troublesome matter, hasn’t iiit?” Chue, her younger sister-in-law, said in a carefree manner.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;This was after they sent Maomao back to the dorms following their departure from Hao’s residence.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;They alighted from the carriage and headed for the Moon Prince’s palace.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What are we to do with the report to the Moon Prince?” Chue asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Since we told them that we’d bring it back, we must report it.” Mamei sighed heavily. If only Maomao made some response then, but it wasn’t like Mamei could go as far as to force the other woman to do so. Chue was better suited at inciting this sort of thing, but she had sent Maomao back immediately after. “And here I thought you would bring Maomao-san all the way to the Moon Prince, Chue-san.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Maomao-san has work tomorrow. Even Chue-san has her reservations on this, you knooow.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Reservations?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Mamei and Chue had known each other before the latter’s marriage, so they would end up speaking like friends once they were alone together.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What do you think will happen if the Moon Prince asks Maomao for her opinion? How would you take it, Mamei-san, if Bakin-san is told to treat a woman as a concubine, even if it’s just for form’s sake?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Ahhh…” Mamei understood. “I would &lt;em&gt;really &lt;/em&gt;hate it.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Riiight? Saying that you respect your partner’s opinions and asking them is ultimately an excuse. Chue-san can only see that as shifting responsibility.”&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yup, exactly.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Men would see it as respecting their partner. Women would see it as shifting responsibility. A difference in views would result in a disagreement. And reconciliation was not necessarily accepting it, even if you did understand the other party’s position.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Maomao-san wouldn’t particularly care either way. Honestly, I think she also understands the advantages very well. When you consider whatever Lady Safflower was thinking, it doesn’t seem like a bad move,” Chue said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“You think so? I found that there were more issues with it, though,” Mamei said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Chue squinted her small eyes into a smile. “Lady Safflower said she didn’t know if her husband would be alive in a decade’s time.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes. Could she possibly mean that she would poison to her husband?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The two of them spoke in hushed tones, but didn’t give out definite names. It was a conversation over-hearers wouldn’t understand.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Even if it wasn’t the lady, don’t you think someone else would do it?” Chue said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“By someone else… next would be her son, or could it be—” Mamei asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What would the concubine do, now that she has lost the tool that&amp;#8217;s her daughter that she had used to improve her standing? She would start raising another small animal, riiight?” Chue was familiar with the darkness of the human mind, more so than Mamei.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“So you mean the concubine would poison her husband next?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes. In fact, Chue-san has looked into where that concubine came from prior to joining this household.” Chue’s intelligence capability was much greater than Mamei.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Mamei was slightly jealous of her eccentric yet capable sister-in-law. At the same time, she thought that her being able to raise children properly, unlike Chue who didn’t even try to hug her own child, was a proof of her blessings.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Maomao-san’s nose is amaaazing. The concubine was actually a courtesan. And not only that, she had been knowledgeable in medicine since back then,” Chue said, while making the characteristic sound of her footfalls. “She was popular, being a courtesan who was both beautiful and well-versed in herbal medicines. In particular, there were stories of regulars coming for her in less than three daays.” &lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Chue placed her index finger over her lips. “Could she have cast some sort of spell?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Spell?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It is a western spell to prevent unfaithful husbands. Every morning, you would add a tiny amount of a delayed-onset poison into your husband’s meal, and then give him the antidote when he returns at night. If he were to ever have an affair and stay out for the night, he would remain unweeell.” Chue was knowledgeable of the West. “There is also method where you don’t use poison but a drug. If so, they would return without waiting for three days.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Mamei broke out in cold sweat over Chue’s speculation.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“After a brilliant herbalist came to the pleasure district at some point in time, her customers traffic dropped and she later got redeemed, you seee.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Could that be…”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes. It was the time when Maomao-san’s dad, Luomen, arrived at the pleasure district. The woman must have done all sorts of things, but when a decent herbalist came, she must have thought that she couldn’t conduct shady business practices anymore while she was at the large store known as Verdigris Mansion, even though it had fallen into hard times back theeen.” Chue crossed her arms and nodded sagely.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Mamei was also aware of Maomao-san’s personal history. Considering how Maomao didn’t know the concubine, she must not have been old enough to remember. “Why didn’t you talk about this before Maomao-san?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Would talking about it have helped?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Mamei was at a loss at Chue’s excuse. Speaking of who it would have helped, it was Hao.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Maomao-san doesn’t want to talk about speculation. She would be troubled if we talk about things that change speculation into conviction, you seee.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The concubine had surely cast a spell to prevent Hao from escaping. Whatever the kind of spell, Hao was bound to gradually weaken.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao must be troubled about whether she should speak the truth or keep it to herself.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Chue-san doesn’t hate villains. After all, we know what kind of people are the fools who try to be upriiight.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The person responsible for the reason Chue couldn’t use her right arm anymore was someone who had been particular about judging criminals under the law.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“We just have to wait a decade, riiight?” Chue said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Mamei understood why the lady didn’t attempt to drive the concubine out with her daughter.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;There was no love or hate in this. She was just using the existence of the concubine as a tool.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It didn’t mean that there were no feelings from the lady at the very start. Just that, at least, there were none now.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was Hao himself who caused it.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Lady Safflower actually wanted to do it, you knooow. Although she can’t rely on her sons yet, they would be more dependable than her husband, and if they’re not greedy, it should be peaceful for some time. The Gyoku clan aren’t that belligerent, so it would be a good topic to hold the third parties in check.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;While they chatted, they arrived at the Moon Prince’s palace.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Basen, her younger brother, was standing in the front of the room.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Has the Moon Prince returned?” Mamei asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes.” Basen guided them into the room.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The Moon Prince was scanning over the documents that seem to the remainder of his work. The lack of Suiren’s presence must mean that she was preparing dinner.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Mamei, is it? How did it go?” the Moon Prince asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Mamei and Chue gave their reports. Perhaps due to Suiren’s absence, Chue interrupted often.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;As expected, the Moon Prince was troubled over the lady’s proposal. “Hao’s lady is capable,” he said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What will you do?” Mamei asked, and waited for the Moon Prince’s response. Whether he accepted or turned it down, it was fine. He had that much power as the imperial brother.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What should we do? How about we ask Maomao for details on treatment?” he replied.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What?” Mamei found herself raising her voice.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What’s wrong?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Nothing… So you mean you will be taking in Hao-sama’s daughter?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Wouldn’t that girl die sooner or later if I didn’t?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;That might be the case but Mamei was boiling over in anger. “Isn’t there another way? The Moon Prince need not take her in. We can just separate the daughter from the concubine, can we not?” she ended up saying such, even though she had decided to bring this matter back for the time being due to its slight advantages. “Does the Moon Prince mean to seed your own troublesome matters to Maomao-san?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“SISTER!&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Mamei ignored Basen who tried to stop her. “In the first place, there is also the empress dowager! Why hasn’t she taken the girl in herself? Isn’t it strange that she is foisting this troublesome matter onto the Moon Prince?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The Moon Prince exhaled. “Do you think Hao would listen to the empress dowager, my mother? You should know that Hao-dono regards the empress dowager as his sister first and foremost.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“However…”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The man called Hao would certainly act with that in mind. He was sure to look down on the empress dowager for being the daughter of a concubine.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“But above being his nephew, I am the imperial brother. The matter was brought to me in the consideration that he would listen if it were from me.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“However, I have qualms about doing something that would make Hao forget himself.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“But Maomao would choose to save the girl over abandoning her, right?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Mamei’s jaw dropped and she looked at the Moon Prince.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I understand very well what Mamei wants to tell me. It would be fine if it’s something that won&amp;#8217;t make Hao forget himself, right?” The Moon Prince gave a big stretch. “From how it’s looking, did you think I was going to support her as a concubine even for form’s sake?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Was I wrong?” That was how Mamei heard it entirely from Hao’s lady.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Mother probably feels bad for her niece. Has Mamei forgotten the kind of things my mother did in the past?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“The kind of things?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The empress dowager was famous for being a benevolent person. She created a place of belonging for the late emperor’s chosen and abolished the surgery to create new eunuchs as well as slavery. Normally, these wouldn’t be easily achievable even for someone in the position of empress dowager, but it was all ultimately implemented by the emperor in consideration of his mother.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;That being said, what resulted from those were…&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;By gathering the late emperor’s chosen, she supported the Shi clan’s rebellion.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The ageing of the eunuchs wasn’t an issue at present with the downsizing of the inner palace. However, it was difficult to gather more eunuchs to supplement their numbers as the only castrated people were the slaves of foreign tribes.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The abolition of slavery. Although it was officially vanquished, it was operating under a different form. The numbers have fallen, but it was now going around in a more insidious manner.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was not necessarily the case that the empress dowager was completely benevolent.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;In ages past, she would probably be known as a villainess. However, as she existed in the same era as the empress regnant who puppeteered her son and the vixen who tried to ruin the country, she had been overshadowed.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Mamei thought about all the things the empress dowager had done until now, and felt that her taking in a niece was still charming.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;And it seems the Moon Prince knew how to deal with the matter too.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“The girl has a weak constitution from malnutrition and poison, right? We’ll just have to do something about the pitiful girl that even doctors had given up on,” he said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes,” Mamei said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“In other words, we can just send her to a place that would give her plenty of nutrients, has people well-versed in medical treatment, and that even Hao-dono can say nothing about, right?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Ahhh.” Chue clapped her hands together. “There is. One such place.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Chue-san, could it be—” Mamei asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“They have fresh crops growing in the garden, or should I say field, that are high in nutrition. They have, for some reason, freeloaders who are well-versed in matters related to mediciiine.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Above all, it is close to her original home,” the Moon Prince said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Mamei finally understood where they were referring to. “Do you mean to send her to Rakan-sama’s place?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yeah,” the Moon Prince said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“But Rakan-sama isn’t the type to do such charity…” No, Mamei heard that he would take in brilliant people from who-knows-where. However, Hao’s daughter was just sickly—she couldn’t see her possessing any talent that Rakan would discover.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“If it’s Rakan-sama, he wouldn’t care even if there are one or two more freeloaders.” Chue understood.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“His adoptive son is Rahan, right? If it’s him, he would take her in if it’s orders from the Moon Prince.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Hahaha, a different trouble might arise, howeveeeer.” Chue let out an all-knowing laugh. “Come to think of it, it seems like Rahan’s older brother is starting to grow a new vegetable. Why don’t we go eat it next time?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I-if it’s a tuber, I don’t want it,” the Moon Prince said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It seems to be a fruit instead. A round red fruit, but its season might be over alreadyyy.” Chue stuck out her tongue.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Based on what she could tell with Chue’s reaction, would this truly be the solution?&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;As Mamei thought such, she thought it was pointless to worry over it excessively.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity" /&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sub&gt;T/N: Looks like it&amp;#8217;s time for the KnH crew to get introduced to the wonders of tomato egg stir-fry 😀&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p class="has-text-align-right"&gt;(&lt;a href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-13-tomato/"&gt;Next Chapter&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div id="jp-post-flair" class="sharedaddy sd-like-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="sharedaddy sd-sharing-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="robots-nocontent sd-block sd-social sd-social-official sd-sharing"&gt;&lt;h3 class="sd-title"&gt;Share this:&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="sd-content"&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li class="share-facebook"&gt;&lt;div class="fb-share-button" data-href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-12-spell/" data-layout="button_count"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li class="share-end"&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-130534757-5137-6766daf967a19' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/index.html?ver=20241221#blog_id=130534757&amp;amp;post_id=5137&amp;amp;origin=shikarito.wordpress.com&amp;amp;obj_id=130534757-5137-6766daf967a19' data-name='like-post-frame-130534757-5137-6766daf967a19' data-title='Like or Reblog'&gt;&lt;div class='likes-widget-placeholder post-likes-widget-placeholder' style='height: 55px;'&gt;&lt;span class='button'&gt;&lt;span&gt;Like&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class='loading'&gt;Loading&amp;#8230;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;span class='sd-text-color'&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;a class='sd-link-color' href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-12-spell/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/main&gt;</description>
